title: Camera to lens adapter
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This Mobius to Zenit lens adapter is intended to serve as a 'long range' microscope, or tele-photo lens. By long range microscope, it is possible to get high magnification, while leaving enough space beneath for working. Note that it is printed with black PLA, but you need to spray some Black 'flat' (non reflecting) spray inside adapter to avoid stray lights.

M42 to Canon camera adapter is used as final thread for fixing, because 3D printed thread is not that good: https://goo.gl/Nwea9b
It is glued to adapter. Printing this thread in 3D is not recommended because it may faild. Mobius camera is light, while Zenit or Helios lens is heavy.

M12x0.5 mm thread on this adapter fit perfectly on Mobius camera with removed stock lens.

Note that there are three holes with M3 thread next to camera (for future adaptation and add-ons, such is FPV TX, battery or something else), and also three holes with M3 thread for possible mounting small monitor.

Bottom part has Imperial thread for direct mounting onto tripod. It is 3/8" (I think they call it so), so that you can fix this tele-photo thing on tripod - achieving good stability.

3D printing setting at my end is: layers height 0.15 mm, 40 mm/s, hotend 212C, bed 70C, support 'everywhere', brim or skirt NONE.

description.text:
UPDATE: have a look at a new, improved version http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2286944

This effector were inspired by Kirill91's one (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1569106), designed for E3D-V6.
I wanted one for E3D-V5 (and E3D-V5 clones), so I made this.
Furthermore, my Kossel mini reached 296mm max height build cylinder, I needed 300mm at least: now with this effector I can print up to 335mm.

Pay attention: I used small axial fan (http://tinyurl.com/l3kpx46), 25mm X 25mm X 10mm.
I also used some magnets (3mm diameter per 3mm height, from www.supermagnete.it) to join diffuser ("diffusore") with base. This should simplify assembly and disassembly.
Nuts in the upper base part are drowned in PLA: this mean you need to stop printing at height in order to insert them in the structure. I will change this in a future version.
A good idea would be to add some kapton all around aluminium hot block in order to insulate it.
A simple thermal and flow analysis has been started and still in development.
The project is still work-in-progress: it is difficult to dismantle hot-end when it is clogged, so I need to change something.

However Pear Effector works good by now!
Suggestions are welcomed, remix as you like (Solidworks 2016 version)!

title: Extension to allow fitting a 40x80mm capacitor with the original battery pack into flashguns Metz 45 series

description.text:
DISCLAIMER: Read this FIRST!

I can't be held responsible for anything that may happen to people or things by using or applying the informations contained in this document: if you do not agree don't read further. You have been warned.

DANGER!

The disassembling of a flashgun is DANGEROUS!
Remember that even disconnected from power and/or removed battery pack, a capacitor for flashgun can still retain for long time HIGH VOLTAGE that can hurt and even kill!

If you decide to disassemble or repair a flashgun please, take all the precautions to avoid incidents, wear goggles, thick rubber gloves and DISCHARGE the capacitor before acting on it, shorting its terminals with a 1000ohm 10W resistor for at least fifteen seconds or more.

THE THING!

Do you own an old Metz 45 flashgun with the high voltage capacitor gone bad?
You can make it to work again by simply replacing it with a new one, but...
The high voltage capacitor is sometimes too expensive to justify the repair for the value of the flashgun or, having been able to find an affordable price on the Internet, is often longer than the original one (65mm), not allowing the insertion of the batteries after its replacement.
As you can see, I already had this problem and I thought that you will find in my project a useful workaround to repair your flashgun with a 40x80mm capacitor.
You can print this extension to be able to continue using the original battery pack.
The only work to do on the flashgun casing, with the help of the 'just printed' piece, is to mark and drill two 2,5mm holes on each of the two little flaps that help to slide the battery pack into its receptacle, to allow to screw the extension on them, as shown in the photos.
To screw the piece I cutted four 3xMA countersunk head screws, leaving 2 millimeters of thread from their heads.
The .STL file foreseen two supports for the internal latches of the battery pack, as you can see evidenced in red in the drawings above. These supports consist of thin walls (0,2mm thick), that must be removed with a sharp cutter, taking care of not cutting off the latches themselves.

Thanks for reading and have good 3D printing time!

description.text:
3 inch is the new 5 inch and that is why I designed a new frame with a new pod that can handle the new power that the 3 inch quads get with there new motors, esc's and fc's.

The frames can be found in the shop of Q-frames on Armattan productions.
https://armattanproductions.com/pages/designer_shop_grid/3914/1273

Some things about the quadcopter.

  • The pod is designed around the cam so it makes that the cam is better protected than with many other frames.
  • It protect the electronics in the frame.
  • An antenna mount to keep the antenna away from the props.
  • Made to fit the Raceflight 4 in 1 esc.
  • Low weight design.
  • Cam angle 25 to 50 degree.

Update:

  • New version added. The Raceflight esc will not fit but that version will follow soon.
    This version is made for the HS1177 style cams and has a cam angle of 15 to 45 degree.

Print the pod that fits your cam and print it in the color you like.

This pod is designed to be printed in TPU. Other materials will brake by a crash.
Nylon is also an option but I don't now how that holds.

The different versions will come soon. I am now working on the HS1177 and Runcam Swift version.
I am thinking of giving the the Foxeer Arow v3 and Monster v2 there own pod design.
There will be also a Runcam Eagle version as it does not fit the HS1177 version.

Remove from the print bed, trim off any excess material, and install wherever 90° bracing is needed, using your adhesive of choice.
Designed in Tinkercad.

title: Printed Filament Filter (1.75mm)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I have printed and tried several filament filters that utilize an internal sponge component. I noticed that the sponge was getting compressed and created a significant load on the filament. Trial and error lead to the current design. Each set of "strands" wipe a different section of the filament as it passes by. The strands are flexible enough to allow the filament to "flow" through without too much drag.

You can use the filter as a "cartridge" for other filter assemblies or use it by itself.

You may need to adjust scaling, depending on your printer settings, to make sure the "strands" are close enough to the filament to create the wiping action without adding too much friction.

description.text:
This is a little gadget I've been wanting to make for a long time. It is used to solder a straight seamless wire splice and is especially handy when making repairs to wires that are still attached to something or situated at an awkward angle.

The problem I've had in the past when making this type of connection is one of control . There is always the need to control 3 things (iron, solder, and wires to be spliced) and only 2 hands to work with. Even tinning a single wire end that is dangling in mid air can be difficult.

The solution I came up with allows me to clamp and position my wires while still being able to manipulate them with my middle finger. I hold my solder roll with my pinkie and control the solder end with my thumb and index finger. My other hand holds the iron. yes it is a bit of a juggle, but once I got the hang of controlling everything, it worked well. If you tin the wires you can then use your thumb to press the wire together. This isn't necessary though as the caps keep the wire firmly in place.

I wanted to make this for splicing wires that are attached to a machine or are in place somewhere. I have pinball and arcade games that are always in need of maintenance and I've been after a solution to this problem for sometime. With that said, this can also be used as a bench tool if you find it fits into your workflow.

I'm still finalizing my design, but I found this version to be perfectly functional. Any input for future improvements are welcome.

Also, I just wanted to mention that I don't think this solution is going to be for everyone as I know there are other ways to make this kind of splice...this has worked for me so I wanted to share.

description.text:
These are two part inserts that can be put in place of 608 bearings in fidget toys. The inserts are designed to hold either a 5/8”(16mm) marble or a 9/16" loose ball bearing. The marbles do not have as much mass as a 608 bearing or the 9/16" ball, they can usually be found for cheaper than loose bearings. Avoid marbles intended for decorations as it’s not uncommon for them to be egg shaped.

Using ABS for the frame and inserts works best as all three parts can be easily welded together using acetone. Other materials can be used, but a two part epoxy will be needed to hold them inserts in place and this method will not be as strong.

description.text: I made this to move the front panel out by 20mm. This uses the original nut and bolt for the bottom. This can accept a nut and bolt for the top if you have the right length or just use a sheet metal screw.

This is a stand alone air filter, redesigned from the ground up but based on the original good ideas presented in "80mm/40mm Fan Carbon Filter v2", thing # 2172962.

This is meant to recirculate/filter the air within a printer's enclosure, not to exhaust it out of the enclosure, to help preserve the heat within the cabinet and to prevent pulling a cold draft of air across the heated build plate.

There are two versions of the filter top which mate to either an 80mm fan, or a 92mm fan. Anything less just doesn't seem to pull enough air to be functional as a filter. Both of those sizes are standard sized PC fans readily available in 12V and 24V.

I up-sized the space inside the box from its predecessor, creating a filter box that is taller and wider to accept more media. The interior is 90 x 90 x 40 (WxLxH), plus the headspace leading to the fan.

The filter box mates to the base via pegs/holes. I undersized the holes slightly, so that if you drill them out with a 9/64 bit the pegs should fit perfectly snug.

Update: I just printed one in PLA and 9/64 was not enough. 11/64 worked, plus a little superglue.

For assembly, the filter top and the filter base are a snug press fit, where the filter top goes around the outside of the filter box. The fan should be mounted to draw air from out of the box, blowing upwards.

Inside the box there's enough space that I was able to fit:

  • 1 layer of A/C foam pre-filter, cut from a roll I got from Amazon.
  • 1 corrugated fine particulate filter cut from a 3m purple allergen furnace filter
  • 3 layers of carbon filter material fabric.

Airflow was good with an 80mm fan. 92 mm will be even better. Overall, either size fan manages to keep pace with the ABS fumes my printer produces. Sitting next to the printer during a long ABS print run, I can no longer smell the fumes or only rarely.

Here's a link to a very inexpensive Carbon Filter you can cut up to use in your newly printed filter box:

description.text:
Presenting,

The Siege Ram,


or as someone else might say,

The Battering Ram


from The Age of Empires!

A siege / battering ram was a siege engine that originated in ancient times and designed to break open the masonry walls of fortifications or splinter their wooden gates.

This is my first model with press fit and moving parts! The Log has a Ram head on its front end which has been obtained from Thingiverse user 'Gedelgo' Thank you for classifying your model as CC-SA licensing so designers like myself could use them.
Here is a link to his model on Thingiverse.

There are 9 different parts for the model which I think can be all printed in one go. This model is supposed to be a desktop toy or a showcase model. It is a close replica if not the exact same. I have tried to add as many details as possible to the model.

Hope you like this model and I would be really really happy if someone could print it off and post it under the 'Makes' section under this model.

Thank you!

Please Note: Because of the details in the model, improper placement can involve quite a bit of post-print cleaning. Slice the model smartly in your slicer and you are good to go.

Post Printing, Step 1:

Once you are done printing all the parts,

You need to press fit the Roof to the Base. I have added small pegs on the Roof legs that will place themselves perfectly into place on the base to secure a Roof-Base connection.

For any of you wondering, the tolerance is 150 microns, which is neither too tight nor too loose.

Post Printing, Step 2:

One more small step and you will be done with the model!

There is one small manual addition to the model; The threads that will hold into place, your Log, between the Roof and the Base.

Notice the semicircular loops on the log and the rectangular windows on the roof top. Those are for looping your threads into place. You will need not more than 15 cms of thick thread for the same.

Once you are done with that step, VOILA! You have your own Siege Ram to display.

Here are some pictures to help you with the same.

#1: Place threads between these semicircular hoops on the Log. #2: After looping inside the Log, pass the threads through the rectangular windows on the Roof Frame and tie to secure the log in suspension.

title: No Drill  Monoprice MP Select Mini GT2 Y Tensioner

description.text:
Inspired by Burner's belt tensioner(http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2204265), this one does not use zipties or need to drill/tap any holes. Using zipties to pinch the belt in place prevents full print bed movement pulls unevenly on the belts, increasing tension.

Installation: Parts are oriented to have adjustment on the rear of the printer, with the front being clipped in place.

Static Belt Clip: When tensioned down this doesn't move, but can be additionally held in place with a 3/4" wide binder clip with the arms removed.

Brace/Slider: Use 8 or 10mm M3 screws with nuts on the inside to hold the brace down. Insert a 25mm or longer M3 screw in the horizontal hole to mate with the M3 nut on the slider.

Printed in PETG, 4 shells, 70% infill. May need to clear out holes to make screws fit.

I used 6mm GT2 belt, it might need to be a little longer than the stock belt.

Parts needed:
2x M3 8mm
1x M3 25mm
3x M3 Nut

comments.text: This worked beautifully for my MP mini v2. I was having all sorts of issues with the stock y-belt design (zip-tying the belt to itself is an awful solution!). This solved the issues with it pulling apart and gave great tension at the same time. Parts printed perfectly at 3 shells and 20% - plenty strong in PLA at those settings to function great. Belts fit in the toothed slots perfectly. Thanks for the design!

description.text:
I love the original Switch controller " Dock" it feels right and works well, but I am not able to use my silicon sleeves on my joycons while they are mounted on the original grip.

I dont want to take of the sleeves every time I attach them to the original grip

So I had a look around on Thingiverse and there are a bunch of great alternatives.
I fell in love with Con U v2 from artobot, he got some awesome designs.

After printing it I was able to mount my joycons on his Con U V2 but even with the silicone sleeves it was to flat and not comfortable to hold for me.

So I remixed his design with another great Design from EbonNebula which had a great grip design and added my own features to it.
I am pretty proud about the outcome, this in my opinion is the most comfortable 3D printed joycon grip so far ;) Also now Iam able to leave the silicone sleeves on the joycons.

The Grip on the Back is detachable and hold in position by a circular Lock.

There are two elevated pods on the detachable grip, you can add two chair felt pads to support the joycons against the applied pressure from your Thumbs.

Fix the " lockdisk" with a common screw, washer and an o ring to apply constant and stable pressure on the locking mechanism.

IMPORTANT:

After Printing you have to cut or file down the sides of the grip mount to make it fit the base of the Comfycon, I made it a bit wider on purpose because not every printer prints the same,but this part has to be a tight fit for a good experience. Use a file and retry more often until you reach the perfect fit.

title: Prusa Mk2 Spool Holder - No Bearing

description.text: I kind of like this one but unfortunately it is hard to find 608 bearing as it is quite expensive compared to procuring screws and nuts. I made adjustment so you only use screws and nuts instead of 608 bearings.

Bearings

These are actually the gear bearing from Emmet Lalish, modified to accommodate to this application. Several models has been exported and adjust them using the openscad script you want.

If you want to use the provided bearing, take note of the last 3 digit number of each model as those are the tolerance in the gear bearing in terms of microns

These are meant to be used with arms L/R.stl which has small hex spacers and you just tighten the screw until it holds down the bearing center and the spacer so the outer wheel able to spin freely.

These are quite tricky as I tried to print different tolerances, some printout resulting lesser friction while some higher friction even it is the same tolerance setting.

Assembly

Assembly are pretty straight forward. It is recommended to use locknut to secure them in place. If you're using "wheel.stl", make sure the wheel can move freely on the screw instead of being held in place without any rotation.

title: Kress 1050 Tool Mount & Dust Shoe v2 (MPCNC)

description.text:
Mount for Kress 1050 (should fit Kress 800 to - please confirm anyone). The mount places the Kress as close to the gantry as possible and works very well. Since the lower part of the mount is exposed to heat from the motor I printed mine in PetG, it may work with PLA but I can't guarantee. Should also work with ABS.

I also made an extended version of the F-ToolMount (MPCNC IE) to download here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1735865

This is a completely new version of the Kress Mount.
In this version I have solved some stuff that didn't´t work optimal in the last version (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1735877 which still works good)
I have also made it modular and cheeper to print :)



My goals for this version:

  1. Easy access to lock button
  2. Integrated touch plate connection
  3. Modular design
  4. Use less filament
  5. Better dust shoe (where the brush, plastic or what ever material you use don´t get in the way of the mill bit)
  6. Easier to print on smaller printers



Pick what you need - Optional dust shoe:

  1. Tool Mount and Clamp for Kress (3D print)
  2. Dust Shoe (3D print or mill with your MPCNC)

The mount is made for M4 nuts and screws.
For the Dust Shoe you need 12 pieces of 12 x 2mm magnets and a tube 40mm x 60mm

If you like the Kress Mount - please tip the designer a Coffeé or some filament ;)
It takes a lot of time, filament and acrylic to made this Kress Mount and Dust Shoe work as expected. Hope you like it!

Kress Mount & Clamp - Assembly

  1. Drill up all holes with 4mm drill on the Kress Mount and the Clamp but DO NOT DRILL THE HOLE IN THE BUTTOM OF THE KRESS MOUNT - If you do you may need bigger screws for the Connection Layer.

  2. If you want to use the Dust Shoe you first need to screw the Connection Layer to the foot of the Kress Mount. You can use any 4 x 20mm screw.

  3. Mount the Kress Mount to the MPCNC ToolMount

  4. Mount the Clamp to MPCNC ToolMount

  5. If you use a touch plate put the cable end in the hole in the front (right side)

  6. Put the Tool with the lock button over the hole for touch plate connection on the front side of the Kress Mount.
    Press the tool all the way down and rotate it counterwise til the tool almost touch one of the screw that holds the Kress Mount to the MPCNC, then fasten the tool and the Clamp.
Dust Shoe

3D print or Mill in your MPCNC. Use Acrylic, Plywood or any other material ~8mm thick. I would recommend that you mill and use Acrylic since you can see through that. The svg-files for the Dust Shoe can be edited with Illustrator if you need to change the diameter of the holes for the magnets or tube. The svg needs points as units to get correct size.

Acrylic - tips and tricks

If you mill this in Acrylic it is important to set the milling order so that the Acrylic don´t crack. Do all the small holes first and then the big holes and last the outer. Take it slow for best result. The setting I used was 700mm/min, 0.3mm per pass. Use no larger end mill than 3.175mm (1/8") since some hole are 4mm in diameter. You need to blow away all the acrylic when milling - use something to blow with.

Dust Shoe Assembly

When you have the Connection Layer and the Brush Layer ready you need to glue the magnets in place with super glue - LOOK OUT that you put them in the same orientation plus (+) or minus (-) in the first layer. When you have glued them in the Connection Layer then put one magnet above each of them so that you know what end that shall be glued in the Brush Layer. When the magnets are in place you need to fasten the ”brush”. You can use brush or something else but I would have used transparent 2mm PVC and it works great (called PVC curtains or strips - search to find online). To glue this to the acrylic you need to sandpaper the face that will be glued to the Brush Layer.

  1. Cut the PVC in the right length and about 60mm wide

  2. Cut the "brushes" - about 1 cm wide and 4 cm long

  3. The PVC will probably curl - Let it curl inwards and sandpaper the area that will be glued to the Acrylic

  4. Put some cable ties together. You can now try to se how it all fit by fasten the PVC with cable tie around the Brush Layer.

  5. Put super glue on Brush Layer sides and wrap the PVC on the sides (magnets up, pvc down). Have a new set of cable ties ready!!

  6. Put the Brush Layer on a surface with the magnets down and wrap the cable ties around the PVC to press it to the Acrylic and let it set.

  7. Glue a 40mm tube about 60 mm long in the front hole of the Connection Layer

  8. To finish everything up screw a short screw 4mm x 15mm from the up side of the Connection Layer in the front. This is to prevent the layers from move sideways. There is also a hole in the back of the Brush Layer where you can screw from the downside for the same function if needed. I have not needed this extra hole.

title: Spool Holder Cones with dual Bearings

description.text:
What is this?

A spool holder cone that is used in pairs to hold a filament spool on a holder with a center rod.

Why did I create this?

One of my printers came with an acrylic filament holder that uses an 8mm rod to hold the spool. To ensure a smooth unspooling of the filament and a centered mount of the spool itself, I designed these spool holder cones. I tried several variations of spool cones from Thingiverse but none of these fulfilled my expectations. So I made my own.

Features

  • uses two 608ZZ bearings per cone and these bearings are the only part of the cone that comes in contact with the threaded rod
  • the washers clamp only the outer ring of the bearings to the cone, allowing them to spin freely
  • the small sleeve clamps down on the inner ring of the bearing so that a nut on the threaded bolt can hold the cone in place while it still can rotate freely.

How do I assemble it?

You will need

  • 4x 608ZZ bearings
  • 8 3x12mm self-tapping countersunk screws
  • 2 pieces of each printed part
  • a screwdriver for the self-tapping screws

Assembly

You will need two pieces of each part for a complete spool holder. You will also need 4 608ZZ bearings.

  1. Insert the bearings into the recess on both sides of the cone (largest part).
  2. Screw the corresponding washer to each side of the cone.
  3. Slide the sleeve onto the threaded rod.
  4. Slide the cone onto the threaded rod. The side of the sleeve with the smaller diameter must face the outside of the cone.
  5. Put a spool on the threaded rod
  6. Repeat steps 4 and 3 for the other side.
  7. Tighten down the cones using nuts on the threaded rod.

How do I customize them?

Edit the various variables in the SCAD file to make the cones suit your needs. I did not test every possible combination of sizes and there are some basic requirements for the minimum size (e.g. you need enough cone to screw into ;-)).
I might add a Customizer-enabled version later on.

This file was initially published in my 3D-Printing Github repository.

title: Linear Rail Z Axis for Lulzbot AO-10x and mendelmax printers

description.text:
The following project will allow you to install 2 fully supported THX Linear Rails in place of the Z Axis 8MM linear rod found on the Lulzbot AO-10x series printers. It also upgrades the Z endstop for additional precision.
PREREQUISITES:
  • You must already have installed seasoe's LulzBot AO-101 Simple 60MM Height Increase Modification http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:97575
  • You need to have completed the Z-nut springs, Lower X end Clamps, and X Idler from my own existing Project: AO-Taz. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:164054
  • an additional 40MM worth of unused X axis belt, or a new longer belt.
    Development thread is here:
    http://forum.lulzbot.com/viewtopic.php?f=16&t=489

After completing the 60MM height increase and AO-TAZ modifications, print 4 Upper Spar mount pieces ( Right and left 2 per plate in STL), 2 Lower Z motor mounts, the Reinforced and extended X motor End Clamp, and the two new backplates (you cannot reuse the existing AO-Taz backplates). At this point, choose which Z endstop to print. If you choose the Micrometer based one, Order one of these micrometers and cut the upper C arm off (http://www.ebay.com/itm/360702635282?ssPageName=STRK:MEWNX:IT&_trksid=p3984.m1497.l2649) Other micrometers should work If that one is no longer available. You will also need to fabricate out of aluminum, or print the 4 angle plates.
You will also need 2 THK RSR12VMA 14.5 inch long linear rails with two carriages each, two 384mm long 20mm extrusions, 4 80/20 TSlot Aluminum 20-2020 x 160mm Long 45 Degree Support 20 Series 20-2565 N angle extrusions (http://www.ebay.com/itm/331078816324?ssPageName=STRK:MEWNX:IT&_trksid=p3984.m1497.l2649) , and potentially some Aluminum plates. You will also need 52 M3 and M5 T-slot nuts, washers and cap screws, some to secure the rail to the extrusion back spar, some for the plastic parts, etc. If you are attempting this project you can probably figure that bit out.
The upper spar mount plates are designed to bolt to the side of the existing upper gantry pieces that hold the linear bearing rod, and are secured using the existing bolts. The lower motor mounts replace the existing units. Please note you will most likely have to unplug your Z axis motors to proceed with that mounting step.
The X motor mount clamp end replaces the existing unit. You will need to extend your belt to compensate for the additional length.
The rail carriages secure to the new backplates using flush mount screws, countersunk, and then are bolted in place on the X ends using the existing Z nut spring hardware and the hardware that was holding the 8MM lm8UU bearings. The Z endstop target will either use the existing endstop hardware, or receive the cut down micrometer end. The micrometer end will need to be drilled to accept 2 holes in the remaining shaft to ensure that it cannot move. The holes for those are not currently part of the printed part, you will need to drill them once you know where they will be on the micrometer remnant itself.
The lower Angle extrusions will be too long to fit. You will need to cut about 15mm off at a 45 degree angle parallel to the existing end, leaving you with a piece that is 130mm long on the longest side.
Bolt everything together, ensure smooth travel on all pieces, and then print away! Troubleshooting:
The wildcard in this setup is the backplate thickness. Assuming you got a really good starting layer, they should be just thick enough to engage the linear rail and the X end clamps. If you find you are binding up on z travel, this may be either too thick or too thin. Also watch that your bearings are parallel and spaced properly. You may also need to move the X end clamps in or out on their bearing rods as neeeded
